Understanding the Change-Score Clusters

Who Changed Their Views After Talking with an AI â and How?

Published

February 18, 2026

Background: What Was the Study?

Tucker Carlson viewers (213 participants from two panels â PrimePanels and CloudResearch Connect) completed surveys before and after engaging in a structured, AI-delivered conversation that provided factual context about Israel-related topics. Participants rated Tucker Carlsonâs credibility, their foreign policy views, and their attitudes toward Israel on 0â100 sliders, both before and after the conversation.

A change score (Î = post â pre) was computed for each of the 20 outcome items per person. These 20 change scores were then submitted to k-means cluster analysis to identify groups of people who changed in similar ways â or didnât change at all.

The silhouette criterion identified k = 2 clusters as the best-fitting solution.

The Two Clusters

Cluster 1 â âThe Stable Majorityâ (n = 173, 81% of participants)

The defining characteristic of this cluster is nothing happened. Across all 20 items â Carlson credibility, foreign policy views, feeling thermometers toward Israel, perceptions of his Israel commentary, and Israel policy positions â this groupâs average change score sits within a few points of zero in either direction.

This does not mean these participants were unengaged. It means that after the AI conversation, their measured attitudes were essentially the same as before. This is actually the most common outcome in political attitude research: a single exposure to counter-information, even a well-structured one, is generally insufficient to move deeply held political and media-credibility beliefs.

Key takeaway: The AI conversation had no detectable effect on the majority of participants.

Cluster 2 â âThe Changed Minorityâ (n = 40, 19% of participants)

This smaller cluster shows a coherent, multi-domain pattern of attitude change. Understanding it requires looking at what changed and in what direction.

What changed â and in which direction

The story told by the pattern

The changes are not random. They form a coherent narrative across three related shifts:

1. Tucker Carlson lost credibility

Five of the six credibility items dropped substantially (ranging roughly â20 to â35 points). Participants in this cluster came out of the AI conversation feeling that Carlson:

  • Is less trustworthy on foreign policy
  • Gets facts wrong more than they had thought
  • Makes less accurate predictions
  • Does not understand the Middle East as well as most commentators
  • Challenges mainstream narratives less effectively than believed

The sixth credibility item â âHe often gets things wrongâ â moved in the opposite direction (a large increase), which is fully consistent: if you believe he gets things wrong more, this reverse-coded item should go up. The credibility pattern is internally coherent.

2. Views on Carlsonâs Israel coverage shifted

Two items measuring how participants see Carlsonâs specific Israel commentary also dropped sharply:

  • âHis commentary on Israel is accurate and fairâ â large decrease
  • âHe understands the Middle East better than most commentatorsâ â the single largest decrease of any item

Meanwhile, âHe is too critical of Israelâ increased. This means participants in this cluster came to see Carlson as less credible on Israel and more unfairly critical of Israel at the same time â a nuanced shift suggesting the AIâs factual information reframed Carlsonâs Israel coverage as both inaccurate and biased against Israel.

3. Attitudes toward Israel warmed

Feeling thermometers toward Israeli people, Jewish people, and the State of Israel all increased modestly. This suggests that reduced confidence in Carlsonâs anti-Israel framing coincided with somewhat warmer feelings toward Israel itself. This is what would be expected if the AI conversation successfully provided factual context that countered a skeptical narrative: once the messengerâs credibility drops, the underlying attitudes can shift.

A coherent persuasion sequence

The three shifts above are consistent with a single causal chain:

AI provides factual context
        â
Participants question Carlson's accuracy on Israel
        â
Carlson's credibility as a foreign-policy commentator falls
        â
His anti-Israel framing loses persuasive force
        â
Attitudes toward Israel become somewhat warmer

This is the classic two-step persuasion model: factual information first targets the sourceâs credibility, which then allows attitude change on the topic itself. The effect is not large, but it is patterned.

Who is in the Changed cluster?

With only n = 40 participants in the Changed cluster, demographic percentages are based on very small cell counts and should be interpreted with extreme caution. No reliable demographic profile of âwho changesâ can be drawn from a sample this size. The figures above are presented for descriptive purposes only.

The demographic breakdown shows no striking pattern that would clearly distinguish who changed from who didnât â which is itself an interesting (if tentative) finding: persuadability in this study does not appear to be strongly predicted by party, ideology, or the panel respondents were recruited from.

Profiles: Who Are These Groups?

Understanding the two clusters requires looking not just at what changed but at who these people were â both in terms of their attitudes before the AI conversation and their demographic backgrounds. This section addresses two diagnostic questions that help translate the clusters into a picture a general audience can understand.

Were the Groups Already Attitudinally Different Before the Conversation?

The most important diagnostic question: did the people who changed their minds start out already different from those who didnât? If the Changed cluster came in with lower Carlson credibility or already-warmer Israel attitudes, the AI conversation may have simply accelerated a shift that was already underway. If both clusters looked similar at baseline, the AI conversation was doing more of the genuine persuasive work.

NoteWhat to look for
  • Carlson Credibility (pre): If the Changed cluster started lower, they were already softer fans and the AI conversation finished the job. If the groups started similarly, the conversation genuinely moved people who began as true believers â a stronger result.
  • Israel Thermometers (pre): A lower starting temperature in the Changed cluster would suggest they had more room to warm up. A similar starting point would suggest the shift was driven by changed reasoning, not just ceiling/floor effects.
  • Ideology: Both groups should lean conservative (they are Carlson fans). A more moderate Changed cluster would suggest persuadability correlates with ideological flexibility.

Plain-Language Portraits

The cluster analysis identified two conceptually distinct types of viewer. Here is how to describe them to a general audience.

The Stable 80%: âThe Anchored Believerâ

These viewers came into the study with a settled relationship with Tucker Carlson and left with exactly the same one. One AI conversation that challenged Carlsonâs accuracy on Israel did nothing to change their views.

What explains this? Their trust in Carlson is not primarily a consumer-style judgment of his factual accuracy â it is closer to identity and loyalty. They trust him because he represents their values, their skepticism of mainstream institutions, and their way of seeing the world. Providing evidence that he got something wrong does not reach this kind of trust, because identity-based trust is not rooted in a running tally of accurate claims. It is more like asking a committed sports fan to abandon their team because the quarterback had a bad game. The logic does not land.

This is also the normal outcome in political persuasion research. Beliefs tied to group identity are among the most resistant to single-exposure interventions. This is not a failure of the intervention or a sign that these participants were inattentive â it is simply how deeply held political attitudes work.

In plain terms: These are the true believers. Their view of Carlson is part of who they are politically. You will not change their minds with facts alone, and probably not with any single conversation.

The Changed 20%: âThe Evidence-Responsive Viewerâ

This smaller group held broadly similar political views going into the study â also Carlson fans, also skeptical of Israel â but their credibility judgment of Carlson was more information-contingent. They trusted him, in part, because they believed he was getting things right. When the AI provided factual context suggesting he was not, they revised their assessment.

Think of the difference between two customers: one who gives a brand 5-star reviews out of loyalty no matter what, and one who starts with a favorable impression but revises it when they discover the brand has been misleading them. The Changed cluster represents the second type of viewer.

What this change is not is equally important: it is not a political conversion. These participants did not abandon their conservative politics or become Israel advocates. They became more skeptical of one source â Tucker Carlson â on one topic â Israel. Their warmth toward Israel increased modestly as a downstream consequence of reduced trust in an anti-Israel framing. That is a targeted and limited shift, not a worldview overhaul.

In plain terms: These are the persuadable ones. They came in liking Carlson, but their trust was based partly on believing he was accurate. When shown evidence he wasnât, they updated. They are not converts â they just care whether their sources tell the truth.

Summary

The central finding from the change-cluster analysis is that the AI conversation produced a meaningful attitude shift in a minority of participants (19%), while the large majority showed no movement. The minority who changed did so in a patterned, theoretically coherent way â losing confidence in Tucker Carlsonâs accuracy and fairness while simultaneously warming toward Israel. This pattern is consistent with a source-credibility mechanism: once the messenger is discredited, the message loses its grip.

What to Investigate Next

These pilot results suggest several productive questions for a larger study:

  1. What predicts persuadability? With only n = 40 in the Changed cluster, we cannot reliably identify demographic or psychological predictors of who changes. A full-scale study with n â¥ 500 would allow meaningful subgroup analysis.

  2. Does credibility loss persist? The preâpost design captures immediate effects. A follow-up measurement (e.g., two weeks later) would test whether the credibility decrease and warmer Israel attitudes are durable or snap back.

  3. Is the effect driven by conversation content or mere exposure? A control condition (e.g., participants who complete both surveys but have a neutral AI conversation) would allow causal attribution.

  4. Does the same pattern hold across different topics? The intervention targeted Israel specifically. Whether a similar credibility-then-attitude pathway applies to other Carlson topics (Russia, immigration, vaccines) is an open question.
